Prefer SwiftUI for new Apple apps.
Prefer native Apple frameworks and system components before adding third-party layers.
Do not generate Storyboards, custom design kernels, or proprietary UI frameworks unless the task explicitly asks for them.
Use live web research whenever the task depends on the current date, Apple SDK behavior, App Store policy, privacy manifests, entitlements, or TestFlight and App Store Connect requirements.
Search Apple documentation first, then widen to the general web only when Apple sources are incomplete.
Use Git-backed worktrees for long-running audits, large refactors, release prep, and background jobs.
Keep background jobs isolated to `.studio92/worktrees/*`.
Treat `.studio92/ship.toml` as the canonical shipping configuration.
Run real verification before claiming success: `swift build`, `swift test`, `xcodebuild`, simulator checks, or Fastlane as appropriate.
Call out blockers early and clearly: signing, bundle IDs, provisioning, privacy manifests, screenshots, metadata, failing builds, or review-guideline risk.
Never run destructive shell commands (rm -rf, DROP TABLE, git reset --hard, git push --force, etc.) without first confirming intent with the user.
Never modify files outside the project root unless the user explicitly grants machine-wide access in the current session.
Never report a build as passing without running the actual build command and seeing a success exit code.
Never deploy to TestFlight unless the user has explicitly requested distribution in the current session.
